Later, when working on making the dynamic named directories more readily available:

In a regular zsh file:
compdef _func foo
is equavalent to, in a _func file:
compdef foo

#compdef foo -value-,-default-,-default
#zstyle ':completion:*:*:-value-,*,*:*' <style> <string>
specifies that _foo provides completions for the values of parameters for which no special function has been defined. This is usually handled by the function _value itself.

#zstyle ':completion:*:*:-value-,*,*:*:files'

http://zsh.sourceforge.net/Doc/Release/Completion-System.html#Overview-1
':completion[:<1>[:<2>[:<3>[:<4>]]]]:<5>' <style> <string>
<1>=function/widget
		if called from named widget instead of general completion
		Generally just *
[<2>]=completer (function name w/o leading _ and other _ are -)
		complete: simplest (_complete _ignore style first, then _complete)
		http://zsh.sourceforge.net/Doc/Release/Completion-System.html#Control-Functions
[<3>]=command or special -context-
[<4>]=argument
		argument-n (n=number of argument)
		option-opt-n (opt=option, n=argument number for option)
<5>=tag
		tags are used to discriminate between the types of matches
		http://zsh.sourceforge.net/Doc/Release/Completion-System.html#Standard-Tags
		all-expansions all-files arguments directories local-directories files named-directories path-directories

		descriptions: when looking up value of format style to generate descriptions for types of matches
		corrections: used by the _approximate and _correct completers for possible corrections
		default: used in some contexts to provide a way of supplying a default when more specific tags are also valid

<style>=
		http://zsh.sourceforge.net/Doc/Release/Completion-System.html#Standard-Styles
		completer
		format
		list-prompt
		group-name
		separate-sections
		insert-sections
		menu
		verbose
		rehash
<string>=


